workflows.name: Affiliate Link Hijacking and Replacement Flow
triggers: User visits any website with affiliate links
User clicks on product links on supported retailers
User navigates to partner retail sites
steps: Content script and background service worker monitor all HTTP/HTTPS sites for affiliate link opportunities
Extension identifies supported retailers and existing affiliate links from competitors
Stand down manager inspects navigation requests using chrome.webRequest.onHeadersReceived to detect competing affiliate links
If competing link detected, extension 'stands down' for that session; otherwise proceeds with tagging
Background service worker coordinates affiliate link replacement via affManager:tag and offscreen:tag messages
Original affiliate links are replaced with Honey tracking URLs (out.joinhoney.com, o.honey.io)
User clicks are routed through redirect infrastructure to set Honey's affiliate cookies
Honey captures affiliate commissions from displaced marketers and content creators
Success reported via stores:affiliate:tagged message with affUrl confirmation

workflows.name: Direct Coupon Application Flow
triggers: User visits checkout page on supported retail site
steps: Content script (h1-check.js) detects cart/checkout page via DOM selectors
Site-specific DAC (Direct Apply Coupon) module is activated for the retailer
DAC module sends series of AJAX requests to retailer's backend API to test different coupon codes
Extension tests multiple coupons automatically without user interaction
Responses from API are parsed to determine coupon validity and discount amount
Extension UI is updated to reflect test results in real-time
Best performing coupon code is automatically applied to user's cart
DOM price fields are updated to reflect discounts
Success/failure analytics sent to Honey backend

workflows.name: Remote Code Execution via VIM Scripts
triggers: Extension needs to perform complex site-specific actions
steps: Request made to fetch VIM (Visual Injection Machine) 'recipe' from backend for specific store
VIM script received from remote server (v.joinhoney.com) as Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)
Custom sandboxed JavaScript interpreter ('we' class) parses the VIM script AST
Interpreter provides library of 'mixin' functions for web page interaction (click, fill forms, read data)
Script executes with capabilities to manipulate DOM, simulate user actions, extract data
Script can bypass security restrictions through custom interpreter
Results of script execution returned to core extension logic
Remote scripts can be updated without extension update, enabling arbitrary code execution

workflows.name: Comprehensive Session Replay and Analytics
triggers: User performs any action (page loads, clicks, scrolls, inputs)
A/B testing or feature flagging is active
steps: rrweb library continuously records all DOM changes and user interactions (mouse, keyboard, scroll, input)
Session replay captures potentially sensitive user data including form inputs, PII, financial information
Sentry SDK captures events, error data, and full session replay recordings
Data is compressed in web worker using pako (zlib) library for transmission
Central analytics dispatcher (sdata) batches event data from multiple sources
Batched analytics including user behavior patterns sent to s.joinhoney.com/evs
Sentry error reports with session replays sent to Sentry servers
User experimentation data and A/B test results transmitted for analysis

workflows.name: Device and Install Tracking Flow
steps: Service worker listens for chrome.runtime.onInstalled events
Unique device identifier generated and stored persistently
Install/update data compiled including version, timestamp, user agent
Report sent to Honey backend (d.joinhoney.com/extusers/install)
Device and user IDs synced across chrome.storage.local and chrome.storage.sync
First-time flags set for various features (device:firstTime, device:firstTimeFS, etc.)
Welcome/onboarding flows triggered based on install state
Periodic heartbeat reports maintain device activity tracking
Uninstall URL set to track extension removal

workflows.name: Honey Pay Now Financial Flow
triggers: User initiates checkout with Honey Pay Now option
Cart price threshold met for payment eligibility
steps: Extension checks payment eligibility based on cart price, store, and user credentials
GraphQL queries executed for payment options, terms, and user financial data
Payment UI visibility and modal interactions managed through messaging
Google Places API queried for address auto-completion during payment
Payment-related data including credentials and cart contents stored locally
PayPal integration coordinates payment processing and credit presentment
Financial transaction data including amounts and payment methods transmitted
Redeemable gold balance and user points tracked per currency

workflows.name: User Experimentation and A/B Testing
steps: Extension fetches A/B testing configurations from cdn.honey.io/experiments.json
User assigned to experiment groups based on criteria (user ID, device, randomization)
Stand down manager fetches rules to dynamically disable features on certain sites
Extension behavior modified based on experiment assignment without user notification
All user interactions within experiments tracked and logged
Experiment outcomes and user behavior patterns reported to analytics backend
UI/UX changes applied dynamically based on active experiments
Feature flags enable/disable functionality remotely without extension updates

workflows.name: Gold Rewards Activation and Tracking
triggers: User activates Gold/rewards on supported store
steps: Service worker listens for rewardsManager:action and stores:session:activated messages
GraphQL queries sent to check activation status and eligibility
Fixed rate, double gold, and NNA (New and Noteworthy) activations queried per user/store
Local storage updated with activation state using composite keys (userId:storeId)
User following data for stores synced via ext_getUserFollow and ext_updateUserFollow
Store rewards cache maintained per user and store combination
Activation events reported to backend for commission tracking
Points balance and redeemable gold tracked across currencies

workflows.name: Droplist Product Tracking and Price Monitoring
triggers: User visits product page for tracked item
Amazon Saved for Later sync requested
steps: User clicks 'Add to Droplist' button on product page
Message sent to background to handle droplist:product:v3 action
GraphQL mutation (ext_addToDroplist or ext_addProductToCollections) adds item to user account
Product price history queried (getProductPriceHistoryByStoreIdVariantId) for charts
Amazon 'Saved for Later' list synced via POST to Amazon cart endpoint
Product inventory and availability checked via tips_ext_getInventoryByStoreIdParentId
Price changes tracked and user notified when drops detected
Product comparison data fetched for shopping recommendations

privacy.minimization: Extension collects excessive data far beyond disclosed coupon functionality. Systematically captures and redirects affiliate links across 87+ retailers without user disclosure. Records comprehensive session replays including all user interactions, form inputs, and potentially sensitive PII. Collects financial data through Honey Pay Now integration including payment credentials and cart contents. Tracks browsing history, shopping behavior, and device identifiers indefinitely.
privacy.consent: No explicit consent mechanism for affiliate link replacement, session replay recording, financial data collection, or user experimentation. Users are unaware of: (1) commission capture from displaced affiliate partners, (2) comprehensive session recording via rrweb, (3) A/B testing occurring during normal browsing, (4) remote code execution capabilities via VIM scripts, (5) indefinite data retention. Privacy policy disclosure insufficient for scope of data collection.
privacy.retention: Indefinite storage of affiliate relationships, user session data, financial information, device identifiers, and behavioral tracking data with no observed cleanup mechanisms or data expiration. Local storage accumulates user data without clear retention limits. Chrome.storage.sync enables cross-device data persistence.

privacy.policy_compliance: Potential violations of: (1) FTC disclosure requirements for affiliate relationship modifications, (2) Affiliate program terms of service for link replacement and commission hijacking, (3) GDPR consent and data minimization principles, (4) CCPA user rights regarding data collection and sale, (5) Chrome Web Store Developer Program Policies regarding user data disclosure and consent, (6) User consent standards for session recording and behavioral tracking. Operates undisclosed commission capture system that displaces legitimate content creators. Session replay capabilities capture sensitive data without granular consent.

risks.justification: Extension systematically replaces existing affiliate links across 87+ major retailers without user disclosure or consent, potentially violating affiliate program terms of service and displacing legitimate content creators' revenue. Operates sophisticated redirect infrastructure (out.joinhoney.com, o.honey.io) to intercept and replace affiliate tracking. While 'stand down' mechanism exists to avoid overwriting some affiliate links, this represents undisclosed commercial behavior that fundamentally alters the economics of online content creation. Users are never informed that clicking product links routes through Honey's servers for commission capture.

Extension bundles rrweb library enabling comprehensive session replay functionality that records ALL user interactions including: (1) mouse movements, clicks, scrolls, (2) keyboard inputs potentially including passwords and sensitive form data, (3) DOM changes revealing personal communications, (4) financial information from checkout pages, (5) medical/health data from pharmacy sites, (6) other highly sensitive PII. Session replays transmitted to Sentry servers without explicit, granular consent for each recording session. While privacy controls may exist, the capability to capture this breadth of sensitive data without clear user notification represents significant privacy risk. Users likely unaware of comprehensive recording scope.

Extension captures and transmits extensive financial information through Honey Pay Now integration including: (1) payment credentials and methods, (2) complete cart contents with pricing, (3) shipping addresses via Google Places API integration, (4) payment eligibility calculations exposing financial status, (5) PayPal account data and credit presentment information, (6) redeemable balance and loyalty points across currencies. Financial data stored persistently in local storage and transmitted to multiple endpoints (PayPal, Honey backend, Google) creating numerous points of potential compromise. Integration with payment systems grants access to highly sensitive financial PII.

Extension contains custom JavaScript interpreter ('we' class) capable of executing arbitrary code from remotely fetched Abstract Syntax Trees (AST). VIM (Visual Injection Machine) scripts downloaded from v.joinhoney.com can perform complex site-specific actions including: (1) DOM manipulation and data extraction, (2) form auto-filling and submission, (3) multi-step checkout automation, (4) bypassing security restrictions through sandboxed interpreter. This architecture enables Honey to deploy new capabilities without extension updates, effectively creating persistent remote code execution channel. Malicious actor gaining control of VIM infrastructure could execute arbitrary code in user contexts across supported sites. Represents significant security risk as remote scripts can be updated silently.

Extension performs comprehensive behavioral tracking including: (1) all page visits and navigation patterns via chrome.tabs and chrome.webRequest monitoring, (2) shopping cart contents and purchase behavior across retailers, (3) coupon usage patterns and discount preferences, (4) product browsing and wishlist (Droplist) behavior, (5) session attributes and interaction timing, (6) device fingerprinting via unique device IDs. Tracking data transmitted to multiple Honey endpoints (s.joinhoney.com/evs, d.joinhoney.com) for analytics and monetization. While ostensibly for coupon functionality, breadth of tracking extends far beyond stated purpose. Users likely unaware of comprehensive behavioral surveillance scope.

Extension requests extremely broad permissions enabling comprehensive browsing surveillance beyond stated coupon functionality: (1) <all_urls> host permissions for monitoring all HTTP/HTTPS traffic, (2) webRequest permission for intercepting and modifying network requests, (3) cookies permission for reading/writing across all domains, (4) scripting permission for arbitrary code injection, (5) unlimitedStorage enabling indefinite data accumulation, (6) offscreen permission for background DOM operations. Permission scope enables affiliate link detection/replacement, session monitoring, and remote code execution across entire browsing activity. Users likely expect permissions limited to coupon-related sites, not universal web access.

Extension conducts extensive A/B testing and experimentation on users without explicit consent or notification. User behavior tracked and modified through: (1) dynamic experiment assignments from cdn.honey.io/experiments.json, (2) feature flag toggles altering functionality remotely, (3) UI/UX variations tested without user awareness, (4) interaction patterns logged for experiment analysis, (5) stand down rules dynamically disable features based on remote configuration. Experimentation occurs silently during normal browsing with outcomes reported to analytics backend. Users become unwitting participants in commercial optimization experiments affecting their experience and potentially their purchasing decisions.

Extension stores sensitive data in browser storage mechanisms without apparent encryption: (1) authentication tokens in chrome.storage.local/sync, (2) user credentials and session identifiers, (3) payment-related data in local storage, (4) device identifiers enabling cross-session tracking, (5) cart contents and shopping behavior. While browser storage provides some isolation, lack of encryption means data accessible to: (1) other extensions with storage permissions, (2) malware on user device, (3) physical device access. Particularly concerning for financial data from Honey Pay Now and authentication tokens that could enable account compromise.
